blame sugar is a phenomenon of its time, finding fertile ground in the era of austerity and its attendant inequalities. Inviting readers to resist the comforting certainties of the attack on sugar, Sugar rush shows how this actually represents a politics of despair, entrenching rather than disrupting the inequality-riddled status quo.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDiscrimination against overweight persons. 0aObesityxPolitical aspects. 0aObesityxSocial aspects. 0aSugarxPolitical aspects. 0aSugarxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh  aausterity.  afood.  agender.  ahealth.  ainequality.  amedia.  aregulation.1 aThrosby, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615156840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526151568423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526151568/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles